title: Differences in food between Europe and North America
content: There is something fundamentally different about food in Europe, when compared to the food in North America. Yes, there are the obvious differences—in Europe the portions seem smaller, they seem to contain less sugar, and meals tend to take longer. All of these caveats aside, I am becoming convinced there is something different about the starches—especially the breads and pastas—there versus here.

title: Hypothesis on the differences in European food
content: Is it different strains of wheat? Is it different pesticides? Is it different ingredients used alongside the wheat? I don’t know. But here is what I observed on my recent trip to Italy.

title: Ability to consume more carbohydrates in Europe
content: Bread, pasta, and gelato seem somehow different in Europe from North America. But this is not to suggest a reasonably carbohydrate-intolerant person like me can consume all he wants without consequence. But I do (and by extension suspect this is true for others) sense I can consume more than I can back home.
